[2026-04-03T08:24:21.641Z] Context
Triads are the most efficient way to unlock the entire guitar fretboard. Currently, the 14-level guitar curriculum only mentions triads in passing (Level 9, as a footnote to 7th chords). Khruangbin's Mark Speer — a key reference artist — builds his entire approach on 3-note triad voicings on top strings, yet the curriculum doesn't teach this systematically.
The goal: add a complete triad system (all 4 string sets, 3 inversions, major + minor = 24 core shapes) as a dedicated new Level 6, AND enhance later levels to build on triads throughout the curriculum. This transforms triads from a footnote into a foundational pillar alongside open chords, barre chords, and scales.
Interactive tools (fretboard visualizer with chord tone highlights, color music trainer in chord-tones mode, drone, piano keys) will be deeply integrated into every triad exercise.
Research Foundation
Why Triads Are THE Unlock (Not Just A Topic)
Research and expert consensus from Tomo Fujita (Berklee, John Mayer's teacher), Rotem Sivan, Jens Larsen, and others confirms triads accomplish three things simultaneously that are usually taught separately:

Fretboard geography: Each triad shape maps to exact note locations. Learning Am triad (A-C-E) in 3 inversions on strings 1-2-3 locates every A, C, and E on those strings across the entire neck. Multiply across 4 string sets = the entire fretboard mapped through chord tones, not abstract memorization.
Chord tone awareness: Because triads ARE the essential chord tones (root, 3rd, 5th), learning them gives instant harmonic awareness — you always know where the "money notes" are for soloing over any chord.
Melodic vocabulary: Arpeggiated triads are built-in melodic lines. Mark Speer's arpeggio practice is literally "taking different triad shapes and moving them up and down the neck."

Why Triads Are Essential for Gene's Genres

Khruangbin: Mark Speer does "three-note chord melody stuff on the top three strings" — literally triads. He approaches guitar "more like a keyboardist and harpist than a shredder," using triad shapes as his primary vocabulary.
Funk/Cory Wong: Intentionally removes notes from full barre chords to create "sparser three-note shell voicings" on two or three strings. The 16th-note strumming engine requires small, precise voicings.
Reggae/Ska: The skank upstroke fundamentally uses triads on top strings. "Their lack of fat is exactly what gives them the light, punchy sound that has made them the standard voicings in ska guitar."
Soul/Neo-Soul: Open/spread triads create the "chiming, pure" sound characteristic of gospel, neo-soul, and R&B guitar.
Band context: Full 6-string chords create mud when coexisting with bass and keys. Triads cut through cleanly — the professional studio guitar sound.

Pedagogical Approach (Research-Backed)
Following Tomo Fujita's teaching order and Rotem Sivan's 10-step system:

Start strings 1-2-3 (universally recommended entry — brightest, most musical, the Khruangbin/reggae/funk set)
Ear before shapes (hear and sing triads before drilling fingerings — the sound drives learning, per Gordon's audiation theory already used in our vocal curriculum)
Root position first, then inversions on same string set before moving to new string sets
Apply immediately to music the student already listens to — not abstract exercises
B-string offset awareness: Shapes on string sets including the B string (1-2-3, 2-3-4) differ from those without (3-4-5, 4-5-6) due to guitar tuning irregularity
Voice leading as accelerator: "Voice-leading triads through a ii-V-I is the single exercise that produces the fastest improvement in both comping and soloing" (multiple sources)

The Math: 24 Core Shapes

2 types (major, minor) × 4 string sets × 3 inversions = 24 shapes
Each string set's inversions chain up the neck: root position → 1st inversion → 2nd inversion → root position (octave up)
Same chord appears on all 4 string sets at roughly the same fret zone = 4 registers of the same harmony


