Part 2: New Level 6 — "Triads Across the Neck"
File: sarah-practice-plan/src/data/guitarStudy/level-06-triads-across-the-neck.js (NEW)
Level metadata:

Title: "Triads Across the Neck"
Subtitle: "Three notes, twelve frets, infinite possibilities — the shapes that unlock the entire fretboard."
Artists: "Khruangbin, Skinshape, Cory Wong, Nile Rodgers"
Review: Checks Level 5 barre chord fluency

Exercise Plan (~14 exercises, ~120 min total):
Follows Tomo Fujita's recommended string-set order and Rotem Sivan's ear-first 10-step system. Each exercise uses the curriculum's established pedagogical template (what/why/setup/steps/feel/wrong/sarah/levelUp) with research-backed why sections.
Block 1: HEAR & LEARN — Top-String Triads (strings 1-2-3: G-B-E)
The Khruangbin string set — where Mark Speer lives. Tomo Fujita: "Start here, spend weeks."
Pedagogical principle: Audiation first (Gordon) — hear and sing the triad before playing it.
Exercise gs-6-1: "Hear the Triad — Sing Before You Play" (~7 min)

Drone plays A. Piano shows A-C-E. Student sings each note, then finds it on fretboard.
Tools: drone: { root: "A", octave: 2, texture: "analog" }, pianoKeys: { notes: ["A3", "C4", "E4"], label: "A Minor Triad" }, colorMusic: { root: "A", scale: "natural-minor", mode: "chordTones" }
Research why: Rotem Sivan step 2 — "Feel/sing the triads before drilling fingerings. The sound should drive the learning." Matches our existing audiation-first approach from vocal curriculum.

Exercise gs-6-2: "The Am Triad — Three Notes, Three Shapes" (~8 min)

Learn Am triad (A-C-E) in root position, 1st inversion, 2nd inversion on strings 1-2-3
Tools: fretboard: { scale: "a-natural-minor", position: 1, chordToneNotes: ["A", "C", "E"] }, drone: { root: "A", octave: 2, texture: "analog" }, pianoKeys: { notes: ["A3", "C4", "E4"], label: "A Minor Triad" }, chordVoicings: { chords: ["Am/tri"] }
Why: "Every open Am chord you've played contains these 3 notes scattered across 5 strings. Now you're playing ONLY those 3 notes — pure, portable, moveable. Tomo Fujita (Berklee, John Mayer's teacher) says: 'Don't memorize. Be familiar with each triad — names of notes, degrees, and sound.'"
Constraint-based learning: Fewer notes = deeper exploration of each one (same principle as Am pentatonic in Level 1)

Exercise gs-6-3: "The C Major Triad — Same Strings, Brighter Color" (~7 min)

C major triad (C-E-G) in 3 inversions on strings 1-2-3
Tools: fretboard with chordToneNotes: ["C", "E", "G"], drone: { root: "C" }, pianoKeys
Compare Am and C triads — same strings, different shapes, different emotion
Note: C and Am share two notes (C and E) — voice leading begins naturally here

Exercise gs-6-4: "Slide the Shape — One Triad, Every Key" (~8 min)

Take the Am root position shape and slide it chromatically up the neck: Am → A#m → Bm → Cm...
Tools: fretboard (full neck view), colorMusic: { root: "A", scale: "chromatic", mode: "explore" }
"This is the same revelation as barre chords — one shape, every key. But triads are SMALLER and FASTER. Three fingers, not four. No barre needed. This is why Mark Speer can move so freely — light shapes, fast transitions."

Exercise gs-6-5: "All Three Inversions — The Triad Highway" (~10 min)

Play Am in root position (fret 5), 1st inversion (fret 8-9), 2nd inversion (fret 12-13) — three clusters that chain up the neck
Tools: fretboard with highlights, drone, colorMusic: { mode: "chordTones" }
"Three shapes form a highway up the neck. Root → 1st inv → 2nd inv → root (octave up). Learn this chain for Am, and you've learned it for EVERY minor chord. This is how the CAGED system works at a micro level — each inversion corresponds to a CAGED form."

Exercise gs-6-6: "Major vs. Minor — The One-Fret Difference" (~7 min)

Compare Am triad to A major triad — only the 3rd changes (C→C#). One fret shift transforms the emotion.
Tools: fretboard with chordToneNotes alternating, pianoKeys showing both, recorder: true
Ear training: play major then minor, eyes closed, feel the color change
"The 3rd is the most emotionally loaded note in music. It determines whether you feel joy or melancholy. One fret — that's the entire difference between a sunny day and a rainy one."

Block 2: EXPAND — All Four String Sets
Tomo Fujita's order: strings 1-2-3 first (done above), then 4-5-6 and 3-4-5 (same shapes!), then 2-3-4 (unique shapes due to B-string offset).
Exercise gs-6-7: "Strings 3-4-5 & 4-5-6 — Same Shapes, Deeper Voice" (~10 min)

Am and C triads on the A-D-G and E-A-D string sets — because guitar tuning is uniform here (all perfect 4ths), the shapes are IDENTICAL between these two string sets, just shifted one string lower
Tools: fretboard with chordToneNotes, drone, chordVoicings
"Your power chords from Level 3 were root-5th on these strings. Now add the 3rd — suddenly you hear major vs. minor where before you only heard power. And here's a bonus: strings 3-4-5 and 4-5-6 share the SAME shapes because they're both tuned in perfect 4ths. Learn one, get the other free."

Exercise gs-6-8: "Strings 2-3-4 (D-G-B) — The B-String Shift" (~8 min)

Am and C triads on D-G-B — unique shapes because the G-to-B interval is a major 3rd, not a perfect 4th
Tools: fretboard, drone, chordVoicings
"This string set sounds warmer, rounder — Skinshape often comps here. The shapes are different from what you just learned because the B string breaks the pattern. That's OK — there are only 3 new shapes to learn."

Exercise gs-6-9: "The Full Map — One Chord, Four String Sets" (~10 min)

Play Am triads on ALL four string sets at roughly the same fret zone, then slide the whole set to Dm, then to G
Tools: fretboard (full neck), colorMusic: { root: "A", scale: "natural-minor", mode: "chordTones" }, drone
"You now have 12 ways to play a minor chord (4 string sets × 3 inversions). You know where A, C, and E live on EVERY string. That's the fretboard knowledge that took some players years to build — and you just did it through 3-note shapes instead of rote note memorization."

Block 3: APPLY — Musical Contexts
Rotem Sivan steps 3-8: Apply immediately to music. Voice-lead through progressions. Add chromatic approaches.
Exercise gs-6-10: "Khruangbin Comping — Top-String Triads with Groove" (~10 min)

Play Am → Dm → G → C triads on top strings over a backing track, Khruangbin-style
Tools: metronome: 85, drone, fretboard with chordToneNotes, backing track
Song reference: Khruangbin "August 10" or "People Everywhere (Still Alive)"
"Mark Speer plays EXACTLY this — triads on the top 3 strings while Laura Lee holds down the bass. He told Guitar World he does 'three-note chord melody stuff on the top three strings' and takes 'different shapes and moves them up and down the neck.' That's your Level 6 vocabulary — you're playing his approach."

Exercise gs-6-11: "Voice Leading — The Smallest Moves Win" (~8 min)

Move from Am to C to G to Dm using inversions that minimize finger movement (1-2 frets max per voice)
Tools: fretboard, pianoKeys, colorMusic: { mode: "chordTones" }
"Voice leading means connecting chords by moving individual notes the smallest possible distance. Instead of jumping to a new shape, find the inversion of the NEXT chord that's closest to where you are. Multiple expert sources agree: 'Voice-leading triads through a ii-V-I is the single exercise that produces the fastest improvement in both comping and soloing.'"

Exercise gs-6-12: "Triad Stabs — Funk, Reggae, Ska Rhythm" (~8 min)

Rhythmic triad stabs: short, percussive chops on top strings with muting between hits
Tools: metronome: 90, drone, rhythmCells
Reference: Nile Rodgers (Chic), Cory Wong, reggae skank
"Cory Wong intentionally removes notes from full barre chords to create 'sparser three-note shell voicings.' His picking hand maintains steady 16th notes; the fretting hand controls which notes ring. And in reggae, the skank upstroke IS triads — 'their lack of fat is exactly what gives them the light, punchy sound that has made them the standard voicings in ska guitar.'"

Exercise gs-6-13: "Chord-Tone Soloing — Triads as Melody" (~10 min)

Arpeggiate triads as melodic lines over a chord progression. Land on chord tones on strong beats, connect with scale tones between.
Tools: fretboard with chordToneNotes, drone, recorder: true, colorMusic: { root: "A", scale: "natural-minor", mode: "chordTones" }
"When you arpeggiate a triad, you're playing a melody that ALWAYS sounds right over the chord. The triad gives you 'safe notes' — the root, 3rd, and 5th — freeing you to take melodic risks in between. This is Rotem Sivan's step 5: 'Use triads as anchor points within scales to create melodic interest.'"

Exercise gs-6-14: "Song Study — Triads in the Wild" (~10 min)

Full song application: play the Am-C-G-D progression (from Level 1) using triads in multiple positions, then the Skinshape cycle Gm-C-A7-Dm with triads
Tools: metronome, recorder: true, fretboard, backing tracks
"You just played the same progression you learned in Level 1 — but now you can play it in 12 different positions on the neck. That's the power of triads: the same harmony, accessible everywhere, in every register. You went from knowing ONE way to play Am-C-G-D to knowing DOZENS."


